Patty Tascarella


Senior Reporter
Pittsburgh Business Times







 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    1334 Pennsylvania Avenue                




See All Homes of the Day





 
























                Thursday, Oct. 17, 2013 -- Mont Handley, president/CEO of PittMoss Development Corp., talks about the mix of organic additives and recycled paper that can replace peat moss in horticulture. It's his own mix and he said that it can help the environment by using PittMoss, Handley says. (Justine Coyne/Pittsburgh Business Times).            














 Enlarge





                PittMoss founder Mont Handley got $600,000 in funding from the investors in ABC's "Shark… more 

                File/Justine Coyne            








 



A Pittsburgh startup that counts three "Shark Tank" panelists, including Mt. Lebanon native Mark Cuban, among its investors has parted ways with its founder and top officer.
Mont Handley, who founded PittMoss LLC and created its namesake product, a peat moss substitute made from a mix of organic additives and recycled paper, is no longer president and CEO, confirmed Michael Matesic, an independent director of the Ambridge-based company.













 Enlarge






                            PittMoss founder Mont Handley got $600,000 in funding from the investors in ABC's "Shark… more 
File/Justine Coyne










 


“We are talking with an interim CEO who could be brought on as soon as next week,” said Matesic, who is CEO of Idea Foundry, an original investor in PittMoss. “The company is actively working to identify a replacement CEO.”




Matesic declined comment about Handley and the circumstances of the change. A call to Handley was not returned.
Handley had experimented with the food processor his mother gave him when he graduated from Purdue University to develop a sustainable alternative to peat moss, working on the project off and on for a couple of decades. PittMoss technically launched in 2011, but two years later, Handley quit his job as national sales director at VisionPittsburgh to focus on his startup full time.
In April 2015, Handley appeared on the ABC-TV reality show, “Shark Tank,” to pitch its wealthy entrepreneur panelists to invest in PittMoss, selling them on the potential of the product, which is used in soil mixtures, demonstrating superior growing outcomes while lowering costs. Atypically for the show, three — Cuban, Kevin O’Leary and Robert Herjavec — came in together. The sharks jointly contributed $600,000 in a funding round where PittMoss raised $1.5 million. The other investors were local — BlueTree Allied Angels, Idea Foundry, Angels with Attitude and Innovation Works.

Patty Tascarella covers banking, finance and the legal industry. Contact her at ptascarella@bizjournals.com or 412-208-3832.












 






