Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    1334 Pennsylvania Avenue                




See All Homes of the Day





 
























                Thursday, Oct. 17, 2013 -- Mont Handley, president/CEO of PittMoss Development Corp., talks about the mix of organic additives and recycled paper that can replace peat moss in horticulture. It's his own mix and he said that it can help the environment by using PittMoss, Handley says. (Justine Coyne/Pittsburgh Business Times).            










 Enlarge





                Catherine Mott, BlueTree Allied Angels.            








 



A rolling stone gathers no moss, but a Pittsburgh company with a proprietary process to manufacture an alternative to peat moss has raised $1.2 million from investors.
PittMoss LLC, based in Ambridge, expects to use the money for working capital.









 Enlarge






                            Catherine Mott, BlueTree Allied Angels.                        










 


"We're expanding our production facility and our demonstration facility needs to be upgraded," CEO/Founder Mont Handley said.
The company currently employs four and expects to add six to 10 in the coming months as it increases daily production of its peat moss alternative from 1 ton to 10 tons to supply commercial growers and home gardeners, according to Handley.




The investors include BlueTree Allied Angels LLC, Idea Foundry, Innovation Works, independent investor Matthew Schneider and an unidentified super angel in Texas. BlueTree invested $560,000, CEO Catherine Mott confirmed.
Handley launched his company in 2011. PittMoss is used in soil mixtures. A sterile product that doesn't spoil and includes recycled materials including paper, it demonstrates superior growing outcomes while lowering costs.

Patty Tascarella covers banking, finance and the legal industry. Contact her at ptascarella@bizjournals.com or 412-208-3832.












 






